ce:section.ce:para:
The morphology and size of the CCHNs were characterized by TEM and FE-SEM electron microscopy. Fig. 1
                         shows the TEM and FE-SEM images of CCHNs in which the average size is determined to be about 30 nm with an almost spherical shape. The results confirm that the nanoparticles are in the appropriate size range for efficient drug delivery. Moreover, the hydrodynamic size and zeta potential (ZP) of CDs, CCHNs, and Sil-CCHNs in an aqueous solution were evaluated using DLS measurement (Table 1
                        ). The obtained results of ZP explain the electrostatic interactions between components of the complex. According to our findings, the CCHNs has a hydrodynamic size of 55 nm, while CS nanogel was 105 nm. The decrease in the hydrodynamic diameter of the CCHNs, compared to CS nanogel after the CDs loading, might be due to the ionic interaction between the -COOH groups on the CDs surface and the -NH2 groups of chitosan, which has compressed the nanoparticles. The average ZP of CS nanogel also declined from +34 to +24 mV after adding carbon dots, probably due to the negative electric charge and the presence of carboxyl groups on the carbon dots. Moreover, after Sil loading into the fluorescent nanocarriers, the surface charge of Sil-CCHNs decreased to 17 mV, which demonstrates the successful loading of Sil into the CCHNs. The fluorescent nanocarrier with a positive surface charge is a potential for theranostic application due to electrostatic interactions between the positive charge of the nanocarrier and the negative charge of the mucosal surface [30].
